{
  "doc_id": "4034",
  "text": "The current investigation advanced the strengths of the two preceding imaging studies targeting CIs in ASD [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] by (a) employing a newly created set of video clips as reinforcement in (b) a well-established instrumental reward task to (c) reliably contrast reward system responsiveness for individual CIs versus social approval rewards. Thus, we tested the social motivation hypothesis of ASD more directly, and we applied more ecologically valid reward stimuli. Using a standard set of static images hypothesized to be \"autism-specific objects of high interest\" versus monetary reward as incentives, Dichter and colleagues [CITATION_3] previously reported blunted striatal responses to both reward types in adults with ASD, accompanied by enhanced vmPFC activation for object rewards. Standardized objects as a proxy for CIs, however, provide a potentially weaker estimate of the neural reward effects that could be identified with individualized CI items. Moreover, instead of simple static stimuli, we utilized, for the first time in this line of research, dynamic incentives that are commonly experienced as more naturalistic and appealing and, thus, may elicit both stronger and more reliable motivational responses [CITATION_4] .",
